max heap:
    A complete binary tree where the value of each node is greater than or equal to the values of its children
Array is commonly used to represent a max heap
Inserting:
    Bubble up the new element until the heap property is restored
    The only rule is that every parent must be greater than or equal to its children. 
    If you insert a value and find it is already smaller than its parent, the "heap property" is already satisfied
The Parent is at index (i - 1)/2
time complexity = O(log n)
Removing:
    Replace the root with the last leaf and bubble down
    : Shape Rule - The last element in the array (the right-most leaf on the bottom level of the tree) is the only node in the entire structure that can be cleanly removed without leaving a gap in the array or breaking the tree's shape.
    We need to swap it down the tree until it is larger than both its children
In Max Element the maximum element is always at the root (the first element in the array)